<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate cost per page for a printer?", answer: "Divide the cartridge cost by its page yield. For example, a $30 cartridge rated for 500 pages costs $30 / 500 = $0.06 per page. For color printing, add the cost per page of each cartridge (cyan, magenta, yellow, and black) together. Include drum or toner costs if applicable." },
  { question: "What is a good cost per page for printing?", answer: "For laser printers, a good black-and-white cost per page is $0.01 to $0.03. Color laser printing typically costs $0.08 to $0.15 per page. Inkjet printers range from $0.05 to $0.10 for black and $0.10 to $0.25 for color. Tank-based inkjet printers can achieve under $0.01 per page for black and under $0.05 for color." },
  { question: "Is a cheap printer always more expensive per page?", answer: "Often, yes. Inexpensive inkjet printers typically have higher per-page costs because their cartridges are smaller and more expensive relative to yield. Higher-end printers, especially laser printers, have larger cartridges with better yields and lower per-page costs. Over time, the total cost of ink or toner can far exceed the printer's purchase price." },
  { question: "How do I reduce my printing costs?", answer: "Use draft mode for internal documents. Print double-sided to halve paper costs. Use compatible or remanufactured cartridges. Switch to a laser printer for high-volume black-and-white printing. Consider a tank-based inkjet for high-volume color printing. Preview before printing to avoid wasted pages. Use digital alternatives when possible." },
  { question: "Should I include paper cost in cost per page?", answer: "For a complete cost analysis, yes. Standard copy paper costs about $0.01 to $0.02 per sheet. Add this to the ink or toner cost per page for the total printing cost. For premium paper, photo paper, or specialty media, the paper cost per page can be significantly higher and should definitely be included." }
]) %>

